K-fold for random forest

library("caret")
X <- replicate(
  20,
  {
  folds <- createFolds(training.data$death1y, k = 10)
  lapply(folds, function(x) {
    model <- randomForest(death1y~.,data=training.data[-x,])
    round(as.numeric(predict(model, newdata=training.data[x,], type="prob")[,2])) -
    (as.numeric(training.data[x, "death1y"]) - 1)
  })
})

hist(unlist(X), 100, col="red")

mean(abs(unlist(X)))
## [1] 0.2896

Xgboost

library("xgboost")
gb <- xgboost(
  label = training.data$death1y == "1", 
  data = as.matrix(training.data[,-1]), 
  objective = "binary:logistic", 
  nrounds = 10,
  max.deph = 10
)
importance_matrix <- xgb.importance(colnames(training.data)[-1], model = gb)
xgb.plot.importance(importance_matrix)

Decision area for age and SLC17A9

K-fold for xgboost

Y <- replicate(
  20,
  {
  folds <- createFolds(training.data$death1y, k = 10)
  lapply(folds, function(x) {
    training.set <- training.data[-x,]
    test.set <- training.data[x,]
    model <- xgboost(
      label=training.set$death1y == "1", 
      data=as.matrix(training.set[,-1]),
      objective = "binary:logistic",
      nrounds=9, max.deph = 10
    )
    round(predict(model, as.matrix(test.set[,-1]))) - 
    (as.numeric(test.set[,"death1y"])-1)
  })
})
hist(unlist(Y), 100, col="red")

mean(abs(unlist(Y)))
## [1] 0.3244

  age=seq(20,90, length.out=200),

)

ggplot(
  grid,
  aes(age, SLC17A9, color=pred_gl)
) + geom_point(size=2)

K-fold for cv.glmnet

Z <- replicate(
  20,
  {
    folds <- createFolds(training.data$death1y, k = 10)
    lapply(folds, function(x) {
      training.set <- training.data[-x,]
      test.set <- training.data[x,]
      model <- cv.glmnet(
        x=as.matrix(training.set[,-1]),
        y=training.set$death1y == "1", 
        family="binomial"
      )
      round(
        as.numeric(
          predict(
            model,
            as.matrix(test.set[,-1]),
            type="response")
          )
        ) - (as.numeric(test.set$death1y) - 1)
  })
})
hist(unlist(Z),100, col="red")

mean(abs(unlist(Z)))
## [1] 0.316

Model stacking

We have picked several prediction models and decided to use the caretEnsemble library to stack them into one, more effective model

library(mlbench)
library(caret)
library(caretEnsemble)
library(e1071)

algorithmList <- c('glm', 'rpart', 'knn', 'rf', 'svmRadial')
seed <- 10

We decided to train our models and verify the outcome by Repeated Cross Validation with 10 folds, repated 5 times.

control <- trainControl(
  method="repeatedcv",
  number=10,
  repeats=5,
  savePredictions="final",
  classProbs=TRUE
)

Now, we fit our models with the training data, using the training control that was defined before. After This, we’ll be able to see the accuracies scored by each model in each fold

set.seed(seed)
models <- caretList(
  death1y~.,
  data=training.data,
  trControl=control,
  methodList=algorithmList
)
## Warning in trControlCheck(x = trControl, y = target): indexes not defined
## in trControl. Attempting to set them ourselves, so each model in the
## ensemble will have the same resampling indexes.
results <- resamples(models)
summary(results)

dotplot(results)

When selecting submodels to be stacked it is crucial for those submodels to have a relatively low correlation. Intuitively, it means that each model is smart, but in a way different from all other models chosen. This way, the outcoming model can learn most from each of the models it uses.

modelCor(results)
##                 glm     rpart       knn        rf svmRadial
## glm       1.0000000 0.5927347 0.1783606 0.6736757 0.7318293
## rpart     0.5927347 1.0000000 0.3506910 0.5662922 0.6852208
## knn       0.1783606 0.3506910 1.0000000 0.4875361 0.3711893
## rf        0.6736757 0.5662922 0.4875361 1.0000000 0.7746019
## svmRadial 0.7318293 0.6852208 0.3711893 0.7746019 1.0000000
splom(results)

There are various methods to stack our models. Below we present three: glm, rf and gbm

stack.glm <- caretStack(
  models,
  method="glm",
  metric="Accuracy",
  trControl=control
)

print(stack.glm)
## A glm ensemble of 2 base models: glm, rpart, knn, rf, svmRadial

## Ensemble results:
